{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638340"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:52:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:52:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17701"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17701"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10415"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77980"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10415"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17701"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63416"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10421"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24326"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24357"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77980"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pupillary light reflex is an important clinical sign that helps assess the integrity of specific cranial nerves and brainstem pathways.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the normal pupillary light reflex pathway?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Light stimulates retina \u2192 optic nerve \u2192 facial nerve \u2192 pupillary dilator muscle","Light stimulates retina \u2192 oculomotor nerve \u2192 optic nerve \u2192 pupillary sphincter muscle","Light stimulates cornea \u2192 facial nerve \u2192 oculomotor nerve \u2192 pupillary sphincter muscle","Light stimulates retina \u2192 trigeminal nerve \u2192 facial nerve \u2192 pupillary sphincter muscle","Light stimulates retina \u2192 optic nerve \u2192 oculomotor nerve \u2192 pupillary sphincter muscle"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct pupillary light reflex pathway involves \u003Cstrong\u003Elight stimulating photoreceptors in the retina, which signals through the optic nerve (CN II) to the pretectal nuclei in the midbrain, then to the Edinger-Westphal nuclei, and finally via the oculomotor nerve (CN III) to the pupillary sphincter muscle\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect pathways can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELight stimulates retina \u2192 oculomotor nerve \u2192 optic nerve \u2192 pupillary sphincter muscle: \u003C/strong\u003EThis pathway incorrectly reverses the order of optic and oculomotor nerve involvement, which would not allow proper signal transmission from the retina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELight stimulates retina \u2192 trigeminal nerve \u2192 facial nerve \u2192 pupillary sphincter muscle\u003C/strong\u003E: Neither the trigeminal nerve (CN V) nor facial nerve (CN VII) play any role in the pupillary light reflex pathway. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELight stimulates cornea \u2192 facial nerve \u2192 oculomotor nerve \u2192 pupillary sphincter muscle\u003C/strong\u003E: The cornea does not contain photoreceptors and cannot initiate the light reflex. Additionally, the facial nerve has no role in pupillary control. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELight stimulates retina \u2192 optic nerve \u2192 facial nerve \u2192 pupillary dilator muscle\u003C/strong\u003E: The pupillary dilator muscle is controlled by sympathetic fibres and is not part of the light reflex pathway. The facial nerve is not involved in pupillary control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis reflex pathway allows for rapid constriction of both pupils in response to bright light, protecting the retina and optimising visual acuity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The pupillary light reflex involves constriction of both pupils in response to light entering either eye due to bilateral innervation.","The afferent limb of the pupillary reflex involves the optic nerve (cranial nerve II).","The efferent limb of the pupillary reflex involves the oculomotor nerve (cranial nerve III) which innervates the pupillary sphincter muscle."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63416"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17701"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63416"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T21:38:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T00:30:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10415"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77980"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https